# MUSTANG module

## Description
MUSTANG (MUd and Sand TrANsport modellinG) is a sediment module derived from 
the IFREMER SIAM / MARS community. It has been coded by Le Hir et al, initially 
coupled with the hydrodynamic model SiAM, then with the parallelized MARS3D 
hydrodynamic model, and now with CROCO since release 1.2 (2022).
The particularity of MUSTANG lies in its ability to simulate, with a 
process-based approach, the behaviours of mixed sediments constituted of 
cohesive and non-cohesive materials. MUSTANG manages sediment with 3 
types of particle classes: 

- coarse particle class (first sediment type) is only transported as bedload; 
- sand class (second sediment type, applies to fine and medium sand) is 
  transported in suspension and bedload; 
- mud class (third sediment type) is transported only in suspension and may 
  consolidate and flocculate. 

Each process treated by MUSTANG contributes to the global sediment evolution 
during simulation. To this aim, MUSTANG computes bottom shear stress (from 
current and waves), settling (time-variable settling velocities depending on 
mud concentration), flocculation (explicit or implicit flocculation modelling), 
erosion fluxes (depending on sand/mud mixture), deposit fluxes, sediment layer 
management, consolidation in sediment bed, bedload transport for non-cohesive 
sediment (with or without slope effect) and morphodynamic. 
Several options are available, differing with layer and porosity managements, 
bedload processes and erosion formulations.

## Features
- Two transport modes: Bedload, Suspension
- Three sediment types:

| Type   | Bedload | Suspension | Flocculation   |
|--------|---------|------------|----------------|
| MUD    | no      | yes        | yes (optional) |
| SAND   | yes     | yes        | no             |
| GRAVEL | yes     | no         | no             |

- Sediment processes: settling, flocculation, erosion, deposition,
  consolidation, bedload transport, morphodynamic coupling, dredging
- Substance module interaction for additional tracers

## References
- Le Hir et al., 2011
- Rivier et al., 2017
- Mengual & Le Hir, 2018

